\section{Introduction}

Despite the challenges associated with its definition, species are, by far, the
most commonly used biological unit to assess patterns of diversity, identify
regions of conservation concern and manage exploited resources. For many
taxonomic groups, identifying species based on morphological characters alone
can be problematic as species limits might be misunderstood. Barcoding, the
molecular-based identification methods that use a short DNA fragment (typically
mitochondrial DNA in metazoans) provide an inexpensive and efficient way to
identify species complexes, and gain insights into species limits. These methods
are efficient as genetic data can carry the signature of the historical
processes that have shaped modern patterns. In particular, the expected level of
genetic divergence between reproductively isolated populations is proportional
to the amount of time since they shared a common ancestor
\cite{Hey2010-IMa2}. However, divergence in mitochondrial DNA alone is
insufficient to conclude for reproductive isolation. Historical interruption of
gene flow between populations might lead to genetic divergence, but without
reproductive isolation, upon secondary contact, these populations will resume
inter-breeding. Conversely, introgression \cite{} and incomplete lineage sorting
\cite{} can mask reproductive isolation.

