\section{Methods}

\subsection{Approach}

The goal of this study is to identify cryptic species in the complex
\textit{Holothuria impatiens}, and to understand the temporal and spatial
dynamics of its diversification.

We use a combination of complementary methods of species delineation following
modifications of the approaches by \cite{Leache2010,Satler2013}. First, we used
the Generalized Mixed Yule Coalescent method (GMYC) to identify putative species
\cite{Pons2006,Monaghan2009}. We then used independent lines of evidence
(morphology, ecology and geographic information) to assess the validity of the
lineages identified with GMYC. In the event that no line of evidence could
separate the lineages identified with GMYC, we used model comparison in *BEAST
\cite{Heled2010,Baele2012} to assign species limits appropriately.

We use this approach as the complex includes both deeply divergent lineages that
can readily be distinguished based on morphological characters, and recent
radiations that are morphologically indistinguishable. The multispecies
coalescent offers a statistical framework that provides an objective assessment
of species limits \cite{Fujita2012a}, even when no other morphological,
ecological or geographical information allows to identify independent
evolutionary lineages. Our study shows these methods can be added to the lines
of evidence typically used in integrative taxonomy.

Additionally, to investigate the history of diversification and the affinities
among the cryptic species within the \textit{H. impatiens} complex, we built a
multi-locus, time-calibrated phylogeny.

\subsection{Sampling}

Specimens used for this study are housed in the Invertebrate Zoology collections
of the Florida Museum of Natural History (FLMNH) at the University of Florida,
Gainesville, FL, USA. A few additional tissue samples with voucher hosted in
other institutions or with no voucher were obtained through collaborators
(Table~\ref{tab:voucherInfo} for details).

Specimens were collected at low tide, on snorkel, on SCUBA or by dredging. Most
specimens were photographed while alive \textit{in situ} or in the lab,
anesthetized in a 1:1 solution of sea water and 7.5\% solution of magnesium
chloride hexahydrate, before fixation in 75\% ethanol. When possible tentacles
were clipped, immediately put in 95-99\% ethanol, and later used for DNA
extractions. These tissues are stored in the Genetic Resources Respository of
the FLMNH.

Two hundred and fifty three specimens were examined morphologically and 216 were
used for molecular analyses. These specimens were collected across the entire
known range of \textit{H. impatiens}: Mediterranean Sea, Carribean Sea, Red Sea,
tropical Indian and Pacific Oceans.

