A striking pattern among the members of the \textit{H. impatiens} complex, is
the differences in the geographical ranges among its members. Some species in
the complex are restricted in their range to an archipelago (e.g., Hawaii or the
Galapagos) while others can be found across the Indian and most of the Pacific
Oceans with almost no genetic differentiation (e.g., ESU1, ESU2). The origins of
these differences can stem from differences in demographics history. For
instance, the low genetic diversity combined with the large range of ESU1
suggest a recent rapid expansion of its range. This is corroborated by the XXX
values from the *BEAST analyses.

If for some species in the complex the range restriction is caused by
geographical and oceanographic conditions limiting the export of propagules
(e.g., Red Sea, Mediterranean), others have ranges that overlap with (e.g.,
Wpac, ESU3, gracilis) or are included within (e.g. Hawaii) the range of a
species with a wide distribution (ESU1). In these cases, dispersal limitation
seems unlikely to restrict their ranges, and instead, adaptation to ecological
conditions are more likely to limit their distribution. It is interesting to
note that gracilis, Wpac, and ESU3 are all associated with continental
areas. For instance, ESU3 is found in Madagascar and Tanzania but was not found
