One of the main questions when studying patterns of speciation is whether modern
species distributions reflect their distributions at the time of speciation. For
marine organisms, and in particular within the Indo-Pacific, this assumption is
particularly difficult to hold as (1) current barriers for dispersal are few in
numbers; (2) the dispersal ability of most marine invertebrates is high; (3) the
current landscape of the Indo-Pacific is relatively recent. For instance, the
faunal breaks observed among species composition of reef-building corals are
only poorly correlated with present-day conditions but are much more strongly
associated with geological features \cite{Keith2013}.

Bowen et al \cite{Bowen2013} suggest that sympatric speciation is possible among
marine organisms. In particular, they cite Rocha \cite{Rocha2008} that
investigated patterns of speciation among grunts (\textit{Haemulon}) in the
Caribbean and the Eastern Pacific that show closely related species occurring in
sympatry. Authors in this study invoke the possible role of the sounds members
of this genus produce in assortative mating.


